
### Introduction

Visual cryptography is a cryptographic technique which allows visual information (pictures, text, etc.) to be encrypted in such a way that the decrypted information appears as a visual image.

We take any image and embed a text message in it which is to be shared secretly. This image is encrypted. Further, the encrypted image is divided into N different shares using K N Secret Sharing Algorithm. These N shares can be distributed, the end user needs only K of these shares to generate the original image. After the original image is generated it is still in encrypted form, it is then decrypted followed by the retrieval of the original messsage.

### Features
##### Image selection
 Users can choose an image from their local device to serve as the cover for hiding the secret message. A user-friendly interface allows for easy navigation and selection of images.			
##### Message Input: 
The interface includes a text input field where users can type the secret message they want to embed in the selected image.	
##### Embedding Process: 
Streamlit widgets enable users to initiate the embedding process with a button click. 
#####  Encryption: 
The image containing the secret message is encrypted first using a random key based caesar cipher and then using RSA algorithm to add additional layers of security.
##### Share Generation:
 Based on the values of k and n, the share division is done.
##### Share Upload: 
Users can upload the generated shares of the encoded image through the  interface.   
##### Share overlapping: 
When at least k shares have been uploaded, they are overlapped and the encrypted image is revealed.
##### Decoding Process: 
The interface includes interactive controls to initiate the decoding process. Visual feedback informs users about the progress and success of the decoding operation.    
##### Message Display: 
Once the decoding is successful, the secret message is displayed on the interface for the user to read.
